sometimes life can seem so shallow, and seem as if your going without a purpose, too often i find myself questing everything that i’m doing. not because i don’t believe in self, but because i’m literally breaking generational curses, while also being the first to do so many things outside the box in my family. 

i have so much weight on my shoulders sometimes, but i will never allow my knees to buckle. sometimes I get so caught up in the moment and forget the little things, i forget to be present. 

i forget about how far i’ve actually come. i get clouded in the judgment of myself. we are truly our biggest critics, but that’s gotta change. i wanna live in light and in love and be loved and be able to love on people, without feeling like my cup is running out, i wanna overflow with love and light. and i’m fully capable of that. it’s a matter of having that self discipline not only with myself but with others as well. 

setting boundaries, not letting people walk all over me or disrespect me and i have to be the same way too. 

i am no longer accepting the things i can’t change. i’m changing the things i can’t accept. 

#growthmindset #growth #motivation #inspirational

A week ago I was sitting at home, and there was an article shared about me, speaking about how I was Arkansas’s 1st Black Rodeo Queen and some of the things that i’ve accomplished at the young age of 23. 

I seen a few former rodeo queens comment on the post and when I say former I mean “2002” state queens. And they went on to go back and fourth and talk about how I “act as if I am still a title holder” and I won one title (competed in several pageants) and now “everyone thinks she knows everything” 

and i found myself kinda feeling low, like i feel like i fight so hard to be accepted by people and organizations that will never truly understand me or the reason the things i talk about or am put in position to discuss are so important. 

like diversity and representation. i thought to myself why keep pushing up or organizations about the lack of diversity they have within their organizations and board members for 2 years i have spoke so loudly…

so a week ago i stopped talking and i started planning, i’m no longer trying to fit into organizations that are copy and paste, organizations that don’t represent diversity and feel inclusive. 

i realized i’m really in my own lane. so i started Miss Rodeo Fort Smith with the support of the city of fort smith Arkansas. In one week I had 50 young women apply for the 1st Miss Rodeo Fort Smith Pageant & THEY ARE SO DIVERSE!!! Sometimes it takes a leader to stand up and take charge…

50 girls for a ‘Rodeo Queen Pageant’ and all I did was make a post. I promise to be the cowgirl I wish I had when I started rodeoing when i was 13. 

we didn’t even budget 50 girls but let’s get to it 🤍🤞🏾

I didn’t just win a title May 5th 2017 - I made BLACK HISTORY that day!!! Won a title that can never be taken from me and given to another person.

NO MORE FIGHTING FOR DIVERSE RODEO QUEENS ILL CROWN THEM MYSELF 😚

THE PAGEANT IS CLOSED ** we reached maximum amount of girls. ❤️

YOU MUST LEAD NOT JUST JOIN.

He was only $5. not because that’s what the market value for calf’s is but because he was sick couldn’t weigh up, rejected from his mom, and needed a lot of attention. 

there’s a huge drought in the beef industry especially in arkansas and oklahoma, so many cattle rancher’s are having to cut their herds rn. 

we get so caught up with our platforms and styling western fashion that we forget sometimes the very reason as to why we are able to love this industry so much. and it’s not because your working with the “top western” brands or influencer’s. 

it’s because of the hard working americans that get up everyday and continue to be the source of feeding america. 

it’s easy to wake up everyday and put on the cutest western boots in your closet and wear your pretties fringe clothes, it’s even easier to be a voice. 

So many of us have a story about that one horse that changed our lives, that one experience that made us love the western industry. 

Never forget why were able to love this industry and get all dolled up for rodeos and western events, it’s quite literally because of the farmers and ranchers that wake up at the crack of dawn and care after the animals that not only feed us but put on a show for us time and time again. 

don’t fall short of supporting our hero’s & our animals. they are so important to our community 🤍🫶🏾 

EAT BEEF. BUY LOCAL.

truly don’t have words for this weekend. My heart is so full. I cried good tears so many times. 

First I wanna thank myself, for believing in myself, for pushing all the way through, for walking it, how I talk it. My showmanship has been unmatched in the rodeo queen world! I say that with confidence. 

Less than 2 months ago I was sharing my personal experiences and struggles within the rodeo queen community, this past weekend me and @mayormcgill crowned the very first Miss Rodeo Fort Smith winners. 

Speechless is an understatement. I went from talking about the lack of diversity and representation in the rodeo queen industry, to creating diversity in representation in the rodeo queen industry, and some of the top western brands helped me do that. 

I accomplished in 2 months what the rodeo queen pageants industry, have yet to accomplish and they’ve been around longer than I’ve been alive. 

I didn’t create a copy and paste rodeo queen pageant, I didn’t have a specific target when promoting my rodeo queen pageant. My rodeo queen pageant looked like how our industry looks, DIVERSE. 

I just made my dreams come true right in front of y’all. I said I needed the support and y’all gave me the support, I said I needed the girls and y’all signed y’all’s kids up, I had people visiting fort smith arkansas from all over the world. I said I would get the sponsors and provide everything and I did that. 

At 23 years old I founded @missrodeofortsmith , and hosted the largest most diverse rodeo queen pageant in arkansas. Run and tell that ❤️ 

Catch us on @knwanews at 9pm & 10pm tonight.

January 12th 2023, Mayor George McGill awarded me the key to the City of Fort Smith Arkansas. 

I didn’t see this one coming, I almost cried like a baby!!!! The love and support that has been poured into me and my organization, over the past few months has be nothing short of a blessing. 

Having some of my work on stage with me next to Mayor McGill, Brooklyn Burrell was 1st Runner up in the Princess Division this past weekend Miss Rodeo Fort Smith absolutely priceless, the way she looked at me…. so emotional. I see so much of myself in her, and I know she’s gonna continue to grow into a phenomenal cowgirl. 

I can’t thank Jurena & Mayor McGill enough, they are a huge part of the reason we were able to have such an amazing event this past weekend. Jurena has blew my above and beyond to pour into our city and young women, and I’m so blessed to have her on my journey, she inspires me so much!! Couldn’t have done this without the both of you!!!! 

Jurena thank you for standing by side, encouraging me, supporting me and simply just loving me like your own. Let’s keep changing the world together ❤️

REPOST• @uninterrupted The Game Needs You... and we love you for it. ✊🏾❤️

We’re harnessing the power of #ValentinesDay and #BlackHistoryMonth by sending love letters from UNINTERRUPTED to Black athletes—those who are laying the blueprint in sports that haven’t historically included them and evolving how culture sees Black faces in all sports. Stay tuned as we’ll spotlight five of these trailblazers. 💥

@jadayiakursh x @uninterrupted • @braylendion 

The Game Needs You.. The Game Needs Me—a letter of self love from Black athletes to themselves and to the game.

1️⃣ @JaDayiaKursh, First Black Rodeo Queen of Arkansas

Dear Me,

I didn’t know a lot of things when I was six years old.
The world was too big to wrap my arms around,

Too complex for my young eyes to see.
But the moment I met my first horse,
I knew that nothing in this world
could beat the power and beauty
of having a good horse under your saddle.

Today, the truest version of myself
Sits high up on weathered leather.
In command and connection with 1,500 lbs of muscle.
Tethered by trust.

In some ways, I’m the first.
First generation cowgirl.
First Black Rodeo Queen of Arkansas.
First to believe in exactly what I can do.
Every ribbon, trophy and sash, a receipt.

But in other ways, I’m history repeating.
A product of deep Western roots,
Of proud Black equestrians before me.
Each fueled by the feeling and freedom of flying.

I ride for me.
But I ride for you, too.
For every Black girl who saddles up after me,
who’ll will one day take Western by the reins and say,
“Let me show you what I can do.”

It started with a horse and a promise.
A guarantee,
that if I could tame 1,500 pounds of muscle,
I could tame anything.

And now, you couldn’t possibly stop me.

The Game Needs You.

Love, Me.

Ja’Dayia Kursh

This is so off “brand for me” but bare with me.

I don’t do drama. Will I address every brand that I believe lack’s diversity and representation, ABSOLUTELY. But drama. Nah. 

Last year I went through some shit. And I addressed it with people who I thought were my friends. And instead of working it out, it kept happening so much that, I blew up. 

Last year I went public and talked about how I was living in a house with a group of people, and one of them kept using the “N” word. After addressing it privately multiple times. 

Instead of my friends putting an end to it, they acted like I was the problem because my roommate was comfortable using the “N” word around me.

I was publicly dragged for weeks, they called me the nastiest names, made up the most disgusting lies to fit the narrative they wanted people to believe. 

I was humiliated on social media because I was subjected to listening to the “N” word be used by my roommate. I was made so uncomfortable.

I was discredited. Not believed. Everyone in the house made a video saying I was lying about my experiences. 

I was crushed. I was depressed for weeks reading all those horrible comments about myself. 

Here we are almost a year later and I’m getting tagged in videos from my former house mates, confirming my experiences because they all “fell out”. 

Imagine publicly humiliating someone with lies and then exposing the “truth” when you fall out with your “friends”. 

I didn’t make this post for any other reason than to remind all the young people that follow me, to BE CAREFUL with this social media stuff. Please be careful. People get on social media and say anything.

They hired a paid actor to discredit my experiences. Only to expose the truth when they stopped being friends. 

Social media is face value. Never forget that. I lost myself for a little bit when I went through all of that drama. 

I’m thankful for everyone that stuck beside me and loved on me, @d_magazine @nataliewhiner thank you for allowing my word to being enough proof to share my story, my word is my bond.

And if you picked a side stay over there. I learned. I healed. I got the apology I needed without it really even being an apology. ❤️

Today, I find myself overwhelmed with gratitude and joy as I reflect upon the Miss Rodeo Fort Smith pageant. It was a momentous occasion, filled with excitement, beauty, and an unyielding spirit that could only be found in the heart of Arkansas.

For me, this event marked a significant milestone in my life. It was my very first rodeo queen pageant that I had the honor of hosting and organizing, a dream that had been nurtured within my heart for years. As the curtains rose and the stage came alive, I witnessed a spectacle that surpassed all expectations.

In the heart of Fort Smith, we experienced an unforgettable gathering of talent, grace, and diversity. This pageant became the largest rodeo queen pageant ever held in Arkansas, a testament to the indomitable spirit of our community and the love we share for the rodeo lifestyle.

What made this pageant truly remarkable was the kaleidoscope of stories and experiences that each contestant brought to the stage. It was a celebration of different backgrounds, cultures, and dreams. In that moment, the rodeo queen crown became a symbol of unity, breaking barriers and fostering a sense of togetherness like never before.

But beyond the glitz and glamour, what touched my heart the most was knowing that my name would forever be etched in someone’s testimony. To be part of a memory, a transformation, or a life-changing experience for another person is a gift that cannot be bought or measured. It is a reminder that our impact extends far beyond the superficial, reaching deep into the core of human connection.

As the echoes of laughter and cheers still linger in our minds, let us remember the Miss Rodeo Fort Smith pageant as more than an event but as a testament to the power of dreams, perseverance, and the beauty that lies within each one of us. May it continue to inspire generations to come, reminding them that their names too can find a place in someone’s heartfelt testimony.

Cowgirl’s Of Color Campout 2023 💖 

My heart is so full. This week I hosted my first Cowgirl’s Of Color Campout. When I say my heart, my spirit, my soul was fed in ways I never knew it needed to be!!!!! 

I started C of C not to divide or limit anyone because everyone is welcome, but to hit that target. I was looking for my tribe, my people, like minded women. And I found them. 

It so hard being a woman of color in an industry that was not build for you to thrive, I find myself picking up the pieces over and over again. But now I don’t have to do it all alone. 

I have never felt more SEEN!!!HEARD!!!UNDERSTOOD!!!! 

I have so much work to do. But it’s so rewarding to have had such an amazing successful event. We all came as strangers and now I have a groups of new friends and a committee for C of C 🫶💖 

I would like to introduce y’all to the OG Cowgirl’s Of Color Campout committee and we are actively planning for next year and setting dates so stay tuned 🤍
WE WILL SEE YALL @ NFR 💖

Never been ashamed of who I am or where I come from. Shoutout to those that believed in me. 

And to the haters one of the biggest part of Arkansas’s First Black Rodeo Queen story is that she came from a mother who had her as a teen & and a father who has been incarcerated most of her life. 

Didn’t come from western roots, 10 acres and a mule and still got to it. Still put them size 8 boots on y’all’s necks. Most of my haters came from families they were grandfathered into the industry and still didn’t do what I did with the same 24 hours. 

Came from pastures of land, eight horse slants ect… and mad at someone who literally was borrowing horses and getting it out the mud. 

You can’t understand my hustle cause you can’t understand my struggle. 

You gotta be hood just to understand me 🤞🏾

Dear Thailand, I’m filled with an overwhelming sense of gratitude for the unforgettable experiences that have touched my heart in profound ways, it was the simple act of riding a elephant that added the perfect touch of magic to my adventure. 

However, it was the encounter with the “Long Neck Tribe” that left an indelible mark on my soul, opening my eyes to the beauty of humanity in its purest form.

The “Long Neck Tribe,” also known as the Karen people, are refugees who have found sanctuary in the hills of northern Thailand. Their culture is steeped in tradition and rich in history, with the women adorned in exquisite brass rings that elongate their necks, a practice passed down through generations. 

These remarkable individuals welcomed me with open arms, sharing their customs, stories, and artistry, offering a glimpse into a world so different from my own.

Witnessing the resilience, warmth, and unwavering spirit of the “Long Neck Tribe” served as a poignant reminder of the profound beauty that exists in our world.

This experience has reinforced the belief that world travel is a profound teacher, offering invaluable lessons in empathy, understanding, and compassion. It has provided me with a deeper understanding of the diverse tapestry of human existence, fostering a sense of humility and gratitude that transcends borders and cultures.

As I reflect on this journey, I am reminded of the words of an ancient proverb, “Most people don’t have empathy for people cause they haven’t met people.” This wisdom encapsulates the transformative power of travel, urging us to seek out new experiences, immerse ourselves in unfamiliar cultures, and connect with the people who call these distant lands home.

The “Long Neck Tribe,” has left an indelible imprint on my soul.

Allowing me to continue seeking out meaningful connections with people from every corner of the globe.

For it is through these experiences that we cultivate empathy, humility, and a deep appreciation for the beautiful tapestry of humanity that weaves us all together.
